  <keyword>sinc</keyword>
  <short_description>Sinc function.</short_description>
  <syntax>
    <syntax_item>c = sinc(m)</syntax_item>
  </syntax>
  <param_input>
    <param_input_item>
      <param_name>m</param_name>
      <param_description
      >input array: scalar, vector or matrix.</param_description>
    </param_input_item>
  </param_input>
  <param_output>
    <param_output_item>
      <param_name>c</param_name>
      <param_description>sinc of input</param_description>
    </param_output_item>
  </param_output>
  <description>
    <p><b>c = sinc(m)</b> returns an array<b
      >c</b> whose elements are the sinc of the elements of the input: <b
      >m</b>.</p>
    <p>The sinc function (normalized) is defined as:</p>
    <latex
    >\text{sinc}(x) = \begin{cases} \frac{\sin(\pi x)}{\pi x} &amp; \text{if } x \neq 0 \\ 1 &amp; \text{if } x = 0 \end{cases}</latex>
    <p
    >The sinc function is the Fourier transform of the rectangular pulse function and appears frequently in signal processing and communications.</p>
  </description>
  <examples>
    <example_item>
      <example_item_type>nelson</example_item_type>
      <example_item_description />
      <example_item_data
        runnable="cli"
      ><![CDATA[c = sinc(pi)]]></example_item_data>
    </example_item>
  </examples>
